\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 04/22/2008 03:33 PMSPIEGEL INTERVIEW WITH MICHAEL BALLACK
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 'Football Is more Aggressive in England'
\par }{\f32 
\par }{\f32 \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Michael Ballack, captain of the German national soccer team, talks to SPIEGEL about his breakthrough at London's Chelsea, Germany's pro\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 
spects in the European Championship and his post-career plans.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 \hich\f32 SPIEGEL: Mr. Ballack, the manager of the national team, Oliver Bierhoff, says that you are a great\'85
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 \hich\f32 Ballack: \'85\loch\f32 talent?
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: That too, of course. Bierhoff says that you will have a great E\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 uropean Championship. Do you think so too?
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: What can I say? I certainly hope so. But even that doesn't mean that we, as a team, will be having a successful European Championship. I was in pretty good shape four years ago, but we didn't win a singl
\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 e match. This time I wouldn't have any problem with not playing my best and winning the title nonetheless.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: We've been hearing good things about you since you reached the semifinals of the Champions League with FC Chelsea. You're being celebrated \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 by the media and fans alike.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 
Ballack: Well, okay. It's always important to be in good shape and at your best at the end of the season, when it's all about the championships. I didn't play for half a year, because of my ankle injury, which is why this seas
\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 on doesn't feel drawn-out to me. I feel fit and I'm highly motivated.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: Are there other reasons for your strong performance?
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: This is my second year in England. You get used to British football, but it takes time to grow into this type of \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 team.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: What did you have to learn?
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: In England they play more directly, faster and more deliberately than in all other European leagues. When you get the ball it has to move to the front right away. There is a constant pushing, even when 
\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 
you're ahead, otherwise you hear and feel this grumbling in the stadium. And when you have the ball, they're more aggressive in England, but of course you also have to be more aggressive yourself. Our game wasn't really that focused on me at first. There 
\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 w\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 ere other dominant players.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: Is there a brutal sense of survival of the fittest at Chelsea?
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: There are more exceptional players than in Munich, and it's a constant fight for positions and roles.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: Have you ever regretted the move to London?
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: No, it's exactly what I wanted. If you do a 5,000-meter run, you're a lot slower by yourself than running in a group. Because you get pulled along during the tough parts. And because you have t
\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 
o keep up with everyone else. You only develop if you have good players next to you and when every game is a challenge. When I was with Bayern Munich, I won the Double three times in four years, and then we were often eliminated early on in the Champions 
\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 L\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 eague. I wasn't excited anymore about winning the German championship yet again. I was looking for a new challenge.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: When you played for Bayer Leverkusen, your nickname was "Herbert," an allusion to the conductor (Herbert von Karajan). When you we\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 
re in Munich, people were constantly debating what sort of player you are. Are you now a modern director?
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: I'm a player who goes into what they call the "gaps" in England. I stand in midfield, play passes, run after the ball, get into the penalty \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 
box. Just like Frank Lampard does alongside me. Is that modern? Winning is modern.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: That's what Otto Rehhagel (former manager at Kaiserslautern) says.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: You learn something from every manager.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: When you were out of commission beca\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 use of your injury, some people in Germany were under the impression that Chelsea wanted to sell you.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: That impression was wrong. At first I even had to defend myself against accusations that the ankle operation was unnecessary and that I had it d\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 
one in Germany without permission. It was a difficult time, during which Chelsea lost two titles. When you're injured you live on the sidelines. You don't train, travel or play with the team. The longer it lasts, the more difficult it is to remain accepte
\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 d\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 .
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: Fear of the future?
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: After three or four months, you ask yourself: Why do I still have pain? You get up every morning and hope that things will improve, at least a little. They try out all kinds of treatment methods and some of them ar
\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 e dead ends. Then you have to go back and start all over again.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: When you were 16 and had a knee operation, a doctor told you that you wouldn't be playing competitive sports anymore. Did you think back to those days?
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: Of course. It could'\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 
ve been over back then. If my career had ended this time, however, I wouldn't have been crushed. I would have just accepted it. I've spent 13 years playing as a professional, and I've made sure that my future is secure. Football is a contact sport, and it
\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32  \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 has its occupational risks.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: What sort of a semifinal do you expect in the Champions League?
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: An open one. Liverpool is focusing on the Champions League. As in previous years, the club is going easy on seven or eight of its main players in the premiership leading up to the semifinals.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: Is that unfair?
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: They have no prospe\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 \hich\f32 cts whatsoever when it comes to winning the title, and they can concentrate on the Champions League. Their manager, Rafael Ben\'ed\loch\f32 
tez, is taking a clever approach.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: Is it true that players refer to Avram Grant, your Israeli manager at Chelsea, as "Av\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 erage Grant?"
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: I've read that.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 \hich\f32 SPIEGEL: Grant was an unknown quantity when he replaced Jos\'e9\loch\f32 \hich\f32  Mourinho, and he's considered a prot\'e9\loch\f32 \hich\f32 g\'e9\loch\f32 
 of the club's owner, Roman Abramovich. Is this noticeable?
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: If that were true, he would have had to let c\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 enter forward Andrei Shevchenko play, because he's considered Abramovich's buy. But he doesn't do that.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: Is the team successful in spite of its manager?
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: Is that possible? The team certainly has enough class.
\par 
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 'German Clubs Haven't Won A\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 nything in Years'
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: Just like last year, three English teams are in the semifinals in the Champions League. Does England rule the football world, or does the football world rule England?
\par 
\par }{\f32 
\par }{\f32 \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: Both. The foreign players raise the standards in the Premier League considerably, but they also play the English way: powerfully, forcefully and with determination.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: Is the Bundes\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 \hich\f32 liga's poor performance purely the result of a lack of money, or are Joachim L\'f6\loch\f32 
w and Oliver Bierhoff right when they say that this is nothing but an excuse for Bundesliga managers?
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: Up to a point, it's possible to shape teams and get them to perform optimally by taking a methodical approach and working systematically. But to play at the very top, you need top players, and they cost money.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: Bayern Munich invested sign\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 \hich\f32 ificantly more than \'80\loch\f32 \hich\f32 70 million ($110 million) and has even hired J\'fc\loch\f32 
rgen Klinsmann as its coach. How do you feel about that?
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: I think it's a good thing that they changed their minds so quickly and that it's now been confirmed that stars are import\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 ant.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: Would you want to be part of it now?
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: That question doesn't arise. I'm playing for an absolute top European club.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: The Klinsmann era as national coach raised high expectations within that national team. And after a few succ\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 
essful qualifying matches, the Germans are already seen as favorites for the European Championship.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: But we're not. I expect to see Italy, France, us and perhaps Portugal -- which has the season's outstanding player, Cristiano Ronaldo -- in the se\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 
mifinals. Things will be tight after that, and little things, even small chances, will be the deciding factors. But the pressure isn't nearly as high now. You also have to be realistic and recognize that the German clubs haven't won anything international
\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 l\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 y in years.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: Jens Lehmann, the national team's goalkeeper, is usually on the bench at his club. Many national players are out of shape.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: All of that can still fall into place. There are tournament teams that rise to the occasion as soon a\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 
s things get going, and there are players who were long out of shape and then, when they join the national team, are suddenly playing the best games of their lives. Why should I complain? It's simply a fact of life that important players are injured. Tors
\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 t\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 en Frings is one of those key players, and he's just come back. If he's ready, then he belongs on the team. And we all hope that Christoph Metzelder will make it, as well.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: He hasn't played yet this year with Real Madrid. 
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: It's not an op\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 
timal situation, but if Christoph Metzelder doesn't make it, we don't have anybody at the moment who could easily fill the gap. We should count our blessings that we have Per Mertesacker as a center back who, at only 23, is already a key player for the te
\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 a\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 m.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: Do you agree with our impression that not all players have continued to develop after the World Cup?
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: Yes, but I have no idea why that is. I'm not constantly playing with everyone, after all. But maybe it's just normal that younger pl\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 
ayers sometimes lack consistency. They used to say that a player had to perform at the top of his game for a longer period of time before being allowed to join the national team, but that hasn't been the case for a long time. When I see how many internati
\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 o\hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 \hich\f32 nal matches Bastian Schweinsteiger and Lukas Podolski already have under their belts -- pretty soon they'll have caught up with record-holding national team player Lothar Matth\'e4
\loch\f32 us!
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 SPIEGEL: Cristiano Ronaldo is also young.
\par 
\par \hich\af32\dbch\af16\loch\f32 Ballack: That's true. And he's been playing at an unbelievable level for the past two years. There is always a path to the very top. But it's steep.
\par 
